Production average monthly for the first 8 months is 1.165M units and would add up to more or less 13.9 M units annually. An increase of production of 1% would push it into the next range (14.2) and an increase of 5% would push it 2 ranges up.

I'm wary of narrowing down the forecast range too early, but July figures (1,167k) are in line with June and as expected from a month ago, giving me more confidence that numbers will move within a narrow band approaching the year end, but still anticipating more volatility and potential increase in the last quarter as supply chokes start to ease.

Half way through the year the numbers are around 7M and things are slowing. During the 2008 recession figures hit as low as 600-700k per month, which, puts the floor around 11M - well below the 13 bucket.

My best estimate at this stage is for continuing market conditions to hold back any significant growth for at least two/three months, and more likely 4-6, leading to volatility around the 1.1M/month mark. In almost all of the five previous years sales have trended lower in subsequent months compared to May, with 2020 being an anomaly for obvious reasons. Very sketchy as an overview but I think the likelihood is for similar this year, with an outside chance of an upturn in the last quarter.Given that there is still pent-up demand and a choke in the supply chain there appears less likelihood of big surprises in the near term imo (similar to the recent Auto Inventory question). Total sales in 2018 and 2019 were c17.5m vehicles, which has dropped during the pandemic. In 2018/2019 c31% of full year sales were recorded in the first 4 months of the year, which based on 2022 data to April implies 15m sales this year. In 2022 the % of 2018/2019 sales to date rose to 91-92% from 81% in the first quarter. 90% of 2018 sales in the next 8 months would result in 15.6m sales this year. This is a fairly narrow range which falls in two of the buckets and I have been slightly cautious in my weightings allowing for some economic slowdown during the year (equally one may argue that supply chains will free up and volumes recover as they are currently supply not demand constrained - only a small increase to 95% of 2018 volumes in the next 8 months is required to push sales into the largest >16m bucket).
Prior is 15.5M with increases typical except for years where there is a recession, where the number can drop.
